tical instability, polarization, and radicalism, the period witnessed the efforts of many German writers to play a leading political role, whether directly, in the chaotic years of 1918-1919, or indirectly, through their works. The novelists chosen range from such now-canonical authors as Alfred Döblin, Hermann Hesse, and Heinrich Mann to bestselling writers of the time such as Erich Maria Remarque, B. Traven, Vicki Baum, and Hans Fallada. They also span the political spectrum, from the right-wing Ernst Jünger to pacifists such as Remarque. The journalistic engagement of JosephRoth, otherwise well known as a novelist, and of the recently rediscovered writer Gabriele Tergit is also represented. Contributors: Paul Bishop, Roland Dollinger, Helen Chambers, Karin V. Gunnemann, David Midgley, Brian Murdoch, Fiona Sutton, Heather Valencia, Jenny Williams, Roger Woods. Karl Leydecker is Reader in German at the University of Kent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Germany20th centuryxPolitical and social views. 0aGerman fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aGerman Writers.  aInterwar Period.  aLiterary Engagement.  aPolitical Role.  aWeimar Republic.1 aBishop, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDollinger, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunnemann, Karin V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunnemann, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuthke, Karl S., econtributor.4c